{"key":"processedPost-10865163","value":{"id":10865163,"first":10859608,"last":10865876,"when":1250370824,"utime":"08/16/09 12:13 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>scifipirate said:</strong><br />cut the light out with tinfoil on the sides and bottom and that won't happen, but fuck it, nice flush!!!!<img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/cheers.gif\" alt=\":cheers:\" title=\":cheers:\"/></blockquote><br />Foil makes the problem worse by reflecting light down and under the substrate.&nbsp; Use black tape or bags, but not foil.<br />Side pinning is usually a sign of a dry substrate, since it pins where conditions are right, which is in the high humidity edge.&nbsp; Substrates will always pull away from the sides.&nbsp; It's not a factor of shrinkage due to being dry though, it's due to the mycelium actually consuming the substrate, causing it to get smaller.<br />Some growers drill holes in the bottom of trays for drainage, and this is a major cause of bottom pinning. I don't know if you did that or not, but just saying so others can learn. <br />RR","title":"Re: Bulk tray.. I got side and bottom pinning like crazy"}}